      "writtenOn": "2020-12-08T02:41:15Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e Really good question and it\u0027s a valid concern.\n\u003e \n\u003e Note that in general, timestamps aren\u0027t really solution, especially if events originated in a short succession by different machines (VMs/Pods/Whatever) and are stamped using machine local timestamps. \n\u003e Google systems can rely on go/truetime API, but I don\u0027t think API is available to us.\n\u003e Most DBs out there rely on various contraptions like vector clocks.\n\nAgreed. Timestamp is not a 100% reliable solution. It just helps alleviate the problem to some extent.\n\n\u003e However, unlike them, CV can rely on an actually consistent DB which can disambiguate any races.\n\u003e Upon receiving a RunStart{id} event, recipient can datastore.Get(Run{id}) and do whatever is necessary based on latest Run state. You can see this with UpdateConfig I used instead of Start/Stop in this CL.\n\nYes. That\u0027s what I thought as well. And even if we do index CreateTime, we still need such disambiguation for events originated in a short succession. I think we can start with this and see how it goes. I will keep event may arrive in random order in mind while coding RunManager :D",
      "parentUuid": "37a4fce6_27b71dd4",
      "revId": "64898e78f11c3bc8f88bbd5e2bad5e831bb9ec82",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba"
    },
